Mexico Stocks: Alfa, Cemex, Liverpool, Wal-Mart de Mexico Drop

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 
2011-09-05T20:29:12Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-05/mexico-stocks-alfa-cemex-liverpool-walmex-fall-modelo-gains.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index fell 3.6 percent, the biggest drop since on
Aug. 8, to 33,880.02.  Retailers: Mexico’s consumer confidence index fell to 93.4
in August from 95.5 in July, the national statistics agency said
today on its website. Economists estimated a confidence reading
of 94.3, according to the median of five forecasts compiled by
Bloomberg.  El Puerto de Liverpool SAB (LIVEPOLC MM), a luxury-goods
retailer, dropped 3.9 percent to 89.55 pesos. Wal-Mart de Mexico
SAB,  Latin America ’s largest retailer, retreated 4.5 percent to
31.12 pesos.  U.S.-related companies:  Service industries  in the U.S.
probably expanded in August at the slowest pace in more than a
year, economists said before a report this week. The  Institute
for Supply Management ’s non-manufacturing index fell to 51 last
month, the lowest since January 2010, from 52.7 in July,
according to the median of 59 forecasts in a Bloomberg News
survey ahead of the release tomorrow.  Cemex SAB (CEMEXCPO MM), the largest cement maker in the
Americas, declined 3.2 percent to 6.11 pesos, the lowest closing
price since March 9, 2009. Alfa SAB (ALFAA MM), the world’s
largest producer of aluminum engine heads, fell 3.2 percent to
144.25 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan J. Levin in Mexico City at 
